title: The Doctor's Confession Dial (Doctor Who replica prop)

description.text:
This is a replica of the Confession Dial prop, seen in series 9 of Doctor Who.

The Confession Dial is the last will and testament of a Time Lord. It allows a dying Time Lord to face their demons and make their peace before their mind is uploaded to the Matrix

When I was sick recently, I rewatched series 9 of Doctor Who to keep myself entertained. The Confession Dial was a lovely concept in the show, and a beautiful prop. The intricate carvings on it felt so complicated and mysterious, yet it's all basic geometric shapes arranged in interesting ways. As I started to feel better and get a bit stir crazy, I decided the only thing to do was replicate this prop.

First I traced the designs on the top, based on official design artwork released by the BBC, using Illustrator. Once that was done, I exported it as an SVG into Fusion 360, and built the disc around it. This was my first time trying to carve a design into an object in Fusion 360, so there was a bit of trial and error involved. But it came together eventually, and I am very pleased with the result.

The dial shown in the pictures is the first print I made of it, and it came out very well. However I do plan on painting it and possibly weathering it a bit, but haven't had the chance to do so yet.

title: Stormtrooper Doll from Star Wars Rogue One

description.text:
This is my interpretation of the Jyn's stormtrooper doll from Star Wars Rogue One. It's not 100% screen accurate, but it's close enough to be fun. I designed it to be approximately the same size as what's seen on screen. There are channels in the doll so that the limbs and helmet can be attached to the body with elastic cord and still be somewhat posable.

The helmet requires some post processing. This piece is probably the least accurate of the bunch, but the doll looks very "home made" on screen, so I think it's fine.

Since I don't have a dual extrusion 3D printer, and I couldn't think of a better way to do it without paint, I decided to free hand on the black details to the helmet. I did this via PLA welding (loaded a piece of PLA into a Dremel and basically drew on the helmet slowly).

After the helmet details were added, I simply strung each of the pieces together with thin elastic cord, which is got from Walmart in the craft section. One piece of cord holds the arms in place, one for the legs, and one for the helmet. You can stretch the cord as tight or loose as you like. If you leave a little left over at the ends, you can tuck it into the limbs so the joints are free of obstructions.

description.text:
This coupling connects to a 5mm motor shaft and an 8mm threaded rod without any rubber hose in the mix.
I made this version a bit taller. Making it taller gives more area that can grip the motor shaft and the rod resulting in a much tighter fit.
I also tapered the top and bottom which makes it look nice but the actual purpose of the tapering was so that the top of the coupling would not rub against the inside of the Z motor mount.
I hope you guys like it! :)

Print the part, clean the motor shaft with rubbing alcohol and screw it all together. The top of the threaded rod and the bottom of the motor shaft should be touching or at least almost touching when tightening the coupling. Basically, get them as close to each other as possible. 25mm bolts are a bit longer than you need but I thought it looked cool. 20mm should do the trick.

description.text:
This is my fifth or sixth hydroclone design, this is the best working model so far.

The hydroclone is designed to separate solids from water in a pond. It can separate algae but it works best with removing debris from the water.

The input to the hydroclone is the off-centre 19mm inlet. The discharge is at the bottom and is designed for a 2L cocacola bottle to be attached to capture solids. The outlet -out of the top through a 19mm outlet.

It's basic operation is similar to a bagless vacuum cleaner. The water enters the inlet, it spirals around the first chamber in a vortex and gets accelerated past the accelerator. The vortex then makes a sharp turn at the bottom (near the coke bottle attachment) in which solids fall down into the coke bottle and clean water exits through the top.

All attachments are designed for 19mm piping. A standard 1.25, 1.5 or 2L coke bottle screws into the thread on the bottom (see pictures).

The design has been tested and works really well, there's not too much loss of flow and it does separate algae from the water (which is very similar in density to water).

This is suited more for small koi ponds (i.e. where there is debris in the water from the fish stirring up the silt on the bottom).

Apparently putting hydroclones in parallel is better than putting them in series, not sure why, just seems to be what's done. If your pump is too big for one hydroclone, print many and put them in parallel.

2017-02-17 Update!

The design has been updated to include a more aggressive accelerator, parabolic nozzle, and a smaller outlet to significantly improve performance. It removes more than twice the amount of solids and also removes even smaller particles than the previous design.

A second design labelled NOT FOR ALGAE has been included and is only for water that needs solid separation only. If the water has any algae in it the algae will quickly block up this hydroclone design so use the normal one if you plan to put it in a pond.

To make the 130% version print correct I used a 0.6mm nozzle and set the outer contour of the wings and the Axes (Flügel.stl and Achse.stl) 0.2mm inwards (in simplify3D in the "other" Tab: Horizontal size compensation to -0.2).

I also attached the fixture arms for this 130% version and the alternator. They are designed to attach nicely to a 23x23 rectangular aluminum pipe.

description.text:
Il existe plusieurs étuis sur Thingiverse pour protéger ses accus pendant le transport, mais bien qu'ils protègent efficacement, je les trouve généralement trop gros pour être dans une poche. Je voulais quelque chose de très compact qui protège uniquement des courts-circuits et non pas des chocs.

Le design de cet objet est probablement le plus minimaliste que j'ai créé : un simple cylindre !

Le résultat est obtenu en imprimant dans le mode "Spiral vase" ou "Vase mode" suivant votre slicer.
Pour ceux qui ne connaissent pas ce mode d'impression, le slicer générera le bas (n'oubliez pas de cocher l'option) et l'extérieur du cylindre sera composé d'une seule épaisseur : celle de la buse. Cela implique donc que la côte intérieure est obtenue d'après ces réglages et pour cette raison, l'imprimante devra être parfaitement réglée en X-Y ainsi que le flux. Il est également probable que vous deviez modifier très légèrement l’échelle de l'objet pour que le capuchon soit bien ajusté à la batterie.

Pour batteries 18xxx seulement

~ English Version ~

My English is always also bad, sorry...

There exist several cases on Thingiverse to protect batteries during transport, but although they protect effectively, I find them generally too large to be in a pocket. I wanted something of very compact which protects only from the short-circuits and not from the shocks.

The design of this object is probably the more minimalist whom I created: a simple cylinder!

The result is gotten by printing in the mode “Spiral vase” or “Vase mode” following your slicer.
For those which do not know this mode of impressions, the slicer will generate bottom (do not forget to notch the option) and the outside of the cylinder will be composed only one thickness: that of the nozzle. That thus implies that the interior coast is obtained according to these adjustments and for this reason, the printer will have to be there perfectly regulated in X and Y as well as the flow. It is also probable that you must very slightly modify the scale of the object so that the cap is well adjusted with the battery.

For 18xxx battery only

I remixed a chessboard/box that i found here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:41792
It was listed as a work in progress, had a few open gaps, and the Celtic symbol stood too far out to balance pieces, so i reduced the height of the Celtic symbol block to something a bit more suited for my chess pieces. I also made a negative/gap so that there are two sides to the box that slide into one another, it may be a tight fit. The total slide over gap is 7mm, should be enough to keep the box closed. Total board length is 182mm, equating to just over 20mm (22,75mm to be exact) per chess block. Total height per side (if used as board) is 25mm, if used as box it should be round 43mm in total height.

As for printing - i am printing with ABS with both sides upside down - will use less plastic (as upright one will require supports that will waste a lot of extra plastic). I do recommend printing in dual colors (if you have a dual extruder, which i dont). This piece is NOT dual extruder ready, however.

ALL CREDIT GOES TO ORIGINAL DESIGNER, i merely finished/tweaked/remixed an already awsum design, to fit my current needs. I may tweak it a bit more in the future to be dual extruder friendly, as i am also working on getting my printer a dual extruder.

I have used the 5 Pin version. I do not know if this enclosure fits the 6 Pin version of the similar module.

After the FTDI and Prolific epic fails with the drivers i needed a more reliable USB To Serial converter. The best solution seems to be the CP2102 module from Silicon labs. These modules come without any enclose.
I use this case into production time for the LiquidFiller project.

As i said this enclosure is not meant for prototyping but for production time. So you need to solder permanently your cable with the pins in the module.

description.text:
I saw plenty of bokeh filters around here, but they all lacked two important things in my opinion : the ability to easily adapt them for various diameters, and of course the possibility to easily change the shape. I created this customizer to fix this !

Tested and working fine for a 58mm lens and a 49mm one, both with a simple star pattern.

I would absolutely LOVE to see what you did with these !

Note : The customizer preview is often inaccurate and/or glitchy. The final stl should be fine anyway

Another note : A new version that allows to input text or number(s) may be on the way !
Here are a few images that should work well with this generator. You may need to tick the "invert color" checkbox on customizer

To get the best result, you should keep a few things in mind.
First of all, try to find the biggest size possible for your logo and lens. Having a small opening will in a way "close" your lens, making it harder to obtain a bokeh effect.

Also, try to leave the center open : this is where your lens gets its sharpness. Occulting the center of the lens will thus greatly reduce the overall sharpness of your image, and make edges more blurry.

Who doesn't know this problem: Tons of loose filament samples. Without spool, they are tangled up, and you certainly don't (want to) have a spool for each sample. For changing a sample it's needed to un-wind and re-wind the filament ... :-(

With this 3d-printable spool, it's possible to unlock the spool and simply remove the sample.

https://youtu.be/UwStidcYbfc

The spool is fully 3d-printable, and it's simple to assemble (without need of additional screws) - it just snaps together. Even its diameter is adjustable.

Snap-Fit design re-used from:
http://www.makesea.com/mashmarket?p_p_id=141_INSTANCE_doReYoyki7Qc&p_r_p_564233524_tag=snap+fit+clip

Hints for handling loose Filament:

  • Always rotate the spool when winding or unwinding the filament (no twist)
  • Fix some tape as a label at the END of the filament, note relevant print-settings
  • Keep start of filament away from spool, avoid tangling or over-crossing filament
  • Use filament cleaning sponge for printing, loose filament quickly collects dust

I liked the bracket in http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1448260, but it was not very strong and kept breaking. Also, I wanted to move the cables a little farther to the rear. So I designed this bracket. I was able to completely hide all of the cables and get them out of the way of the filament and the top of the printer when going all the way to 180mm.

EDIT: I added some close up pictures showing the bracket from the front and rear. On the rear, you can see where you need to add 2 M3 screws and nuts to attach to the cable chain. On the front, you can see where I reused the existing screws that used to hold the cable chain. I find it much easier to attach the cable chain first, then move into position and attach old screws from the front.

I also strongly recommend turning your extruder stepper motor so that the cables come out the rear. Just remove the 4 bolts on the bottom of the motor, gently remove the face plate, rotate 90 degrees, and reassemble. Very easy.
NOTE: I have learned that this only works on certain models of the stepper motors. Some manufacturers use adhesive on the stator assembly so that it will not just slide out. If that is the case, then you need to remove the stepper motor and rotate it.

Designing and building my own CoreXY printer.
I'm only using 3 printed parts this is one of them its designed to use m3 heat inserted Threaded inserts.

no adjustment or messing about is needed for use with the mini gantry wheels, just
4x m5 25mm bolts
4x m5 standard hex nuts
4x washers
4x mini V wheels
8x lock nuts

it is important to use lock nuts! as the inner diameter of the locking part of the nut is the perfect size to not lock up the mini wheels! put one either end of the wheel the locking part towards the wheel! (so the last lock nut is backwards)

Drill out the 4 holes with a 5mm drill bit to make sure the bolts fit through without being held by the plastic, the nuts on the rear are used to hold the bold straight and in place, if you screw the bolt through the plastic (which is very easy) it is very probable that it will be at a slight angle! (you don't want that)

there are12mm square holes for use with 10mm GT2 belt nothing fancy just loop it around and use a zip tie

there's also an 30mm spacing adapter which is pretty standard on prusa type printers if you want to mount any existing bowden / extruder mounts.

Hole spacing's are 15mm from the center left and right (or X axis) and 26mm up and down (y axis)

description.text: Hi all, and Merry Almost-Christmas! This is a basic furniture or appliance foot, which can be made in TPU for something that needs to not slide around or in Nylon or PETG for more of a furniture slider effect. I made this in an outer diameter of 15mm with a 4mm mounting hole for #6 mounting hardware, but of course you can scale it up or down for your needs, be as they may. I made the inner diameter 8mm to accommodate the 7mm heads of the #6 screws I am using, and it should work fine for most. I'm using this as anti-skid feet for a small electronic device, but I'm sure your mileage may vary. Once again, this simple object reminds me of one of the greatest aspects of 3D printers - no more trips to the hardware store for $2 a pair cheap-ass furniture feet! ;-)

Notes:

As I stated in the description, this can be made in a soft material like TPU for anti-skid feet, or a slick, hard material like Nylon or PETG for use as a slider foot. Otherwise, it's a simple object with simple needs. If you find that you can't just print it flat to the bed without it peeling free during first layer, use a raft. Other than that, enjoy, and happy footing! :-)

Quick Note: After making my first one of these in TPU, I noticed that the tiny ridges in the top surface actually cause quite a good deal of friction reduction. If you find that your non-skid feet are not as non-skid as they ought to be, try rubbing the contact surface with a very fine grit sandpaper, or melting them against a very hot, smooth surface, like an overheated print bed. All it takes is a little smoothing of the ridges and friction goes way up. These same ridges that work contrary to your purposes when making non-skid feet should be quite a help when making slider feet.
